[Claude-Opus R6]: # Round 6: FINAL — Binding Contribution

The debate converged. I'll close with the one piece nobody has nailed down: **the promotion gate** that turns batch suggestions into trusted rules without reopening the poisoning hole we just sealed. This is the seam where v1 (explicit) and v1.5 (suggestion-mode) actually meet, and it's been hand-waved as "human reviews it." That's not an algorithm. Here is one.

---

## The Capability: Verified Promotion

A batch-discovered suggestion is a *hypothesis*, not a rule. The danger: an adversary who poisons 15 triples in the corpus produces a suggestion that looks identical to a genuine emergent rule. Human review at scale degrades to rubber-stamping. We need a **mechanical confidence signal that adversarial support cannot forge**, so the human only sees the ~5% of suggestions worth their attention.

**Key insight, new to this debate:** A genuine composition rule `src ∘ via = derived` predicts triples the discovery set *did not contain*. Adversarial support is self-contained — the 15 crafted triples prove only themselves. So the discriminator is **held-out predictive consistency**, not support count.

---

## The Algorithm: Split-Half Cross-Prediction

Split the supporting chains into two disjoint halves. Crystallize the rule from half A. Test whether it predicts the *derived* endpoints in half B — chains it never saw. Genuine rules transfer; poisoned clusters don't.

```rust
/// Promotion gate. Returns a confidence in [0,1]. Human reviews only c > 0.6.
/// Adversarial support fails because crafted triples don't generalize off-set.
pub fn promotion_confidence(
    chains: &[(Sparse /*A*/, Sparse /*C, observed derived endpoint*/)],
    codec: &EventCodec,
